-- Foreign Investors Buy Net 1.24 Billion Rupees of Indian Stocks
-- B y   P a r e s h   J a t a k i a
-- 2012-08-23T11:56:05Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-08-23/foreign-investors-buy-net-1-24-billion-rupees-of-indian-stocks.html
Overseas  investors  bought a net  1.24
billion rupees  ($22.3 million) of Indian stocks yesterday,
raising their investment in the equities this year to 586.2
billion rupees, according to the nation’s market regulator.  Foreigners bought 15.5 billion rupees of shares and sold
14.3 billion rupees, the Securities & Exchange Board of  India 
said on its  website  today. They invested 102.7 billion rupees in
stocks last month.  Foreign funds bought a net 446 million rupees of bonds,
taking total inflow into debt this year to 250.6 billion rupees,
the data  show .  India’s $1.1 trillion stock market,  Asia ’s fifth-biggest,
is influenced by flows from overseas. Flows surged to a record
in 2010, making the  BSE India Sensitive Index (SENSEX)  the best performer
among the world’s top 10 markets. The largest-ever outflow in
2008 led to the biggest annual slump of 52 percent.  Foreigners have invested 5.03 trillion rupees in stocks and
1.458 trillion rupees in bonds since they were allowed into the
country in 1993.  The regulator provides data on shares bought and sold by
large investors, including trades in the primary and secondary
markets, with a delay of at least a day.  To contact the reporter on this story:
